summary.seg: This illuminated Gospel Book with Evangelist portraits has been in England since the Middle Ages: it was brought there in the thirteenth century at the behest of the scholar and bishop Robert Grosseteste (ca. 1179-1253), a fundamental figure in introducing the study of Greek into thirteenth-century England. He collected Greek manuscripts, which he had brought from Greece and elsewhere; among them is another manuscript now in Cambridge, University Library, MS Ff.1.24 containing the Testaments of the Twelve Patriarchs.

Gonville and Caius College MS 403/412 contains the four Gospels without any prefatory matter or tables. The illumination is incomplete: only the portraits of Mark and Luke are extant; blank spaces were left for four headpieces, which were never filled. The illumination of this manuscript belongs to the so-called 'decorative style' (previously also known as 'Karahissar group' or 'Nicaea school'), extensively studied by Annemarie Weyl Carr (in particular Weyl Carr 1982; 1987; 1991). This is a Byzantine provincial style, widespraed between the 12th and 13th centuries in the Cyprus-Palestinian area. The script and the layout also point to this period and area: the script belongs to the style epsilon à pseudo-ligatures basses which has been linked with the areas of Palestine and Cyprus, between the end of the 12th and the beginning of the 13th century (see Canart 1981, pp. 46, 50-51; see Hands for further details and bibliography).

support.material: Parchment ( FHHF), of medium thickness. There are a few holes formed during the production of the parchment.
ff. [i]-[ii], [iii]-[iv] : Western paper; these are later endleaves, which were added with the binding.

foliation.p: Pagination in ink on the top right hand corner recto. The number 1 is not extant due to damage of the leaf; no. 21 is repeated as 21b; the pagination is interrupted at p. 291; afterwards numbers are written in pencil, with a few exceptions, every 10 pages; wrong page numbers in pencil were erased and corrected, in pencil as well, at pp. 373-379; two paper unnumbered endleaves both at the beginning and at the end of the manuscript came with the binding: ff. [i]-[ii] + pp. [1]-[2], 3-21, 21b-[22b], 23-291, [292]-[300], 301, [302]-[312], 313, [314]-[320], 321, [322]-[330], 331, [332]-[340], 341, [342]-[350], 351, [352]-[360], 361, [362]-[370], 371-381, [382]-[390], 391, [392]-[400], 401, [402]-[410], 411, [412]-[420], 421, [422]-[430], 431, [432]-[440], 441, [442]-[450], 451, [452]-[460], 462, [463]-[472] + ff. [iii]-[iv]
Throughout the manuscript, in the upper margins, there are running titles written by Robert Grosseteste (Harrison Thompson 1940, p. 29; Callus 1955, p. 135).

collation.p: The manuscript is formed mostly by quaternions. The leaf formed by pp. 471-[472] seems to have been pasted to a bifolium formed by ff. 467-[468]/469-[470].

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript is in fair condition. The first and last leaves are stained; occasionally, throughout the manuscript, there are ink and brown stains. The parchment, in the final part of the manuscript, tends to creasing. Pigments in the two illuminations have been damaged in some places.

layoutDesc.layout:
A single column of 22-24 lines. 140-145 100
Pricking survives in the upper and lower margins, but much has been lost to cropping. Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 9, type Leroy 32C1. Text hangs from the lines.

handNote.p: pp. 1-[470] Hand A: the text has been written in a minuscule script, vertical, hanging from the lines, calligraphic, belonging to the traditional type; letters tend to have a rectangular form; some are larger, such as kappa, majuscule delta, phi, csi, chi, theta. The script shows so-called pseudo-ligatures, in particular for the letter epsilon, in its majuscule form, whose central horizontal stroke stretches to the right and touches the base of the next letter; the lower edge of minuscule gamma tends to be placed to the left with respect to the vertical axis of the script. These features have been identified as characteristics of the style ' epsilon à pseudo-ligatures basses' which has been linked with the area of Palestine and Cyprus, between the end of the 12th and the beginning of the 13th c. The script has, in particular, affinity to the rectangular stylisation of this type of script (see Canart 1981, pp. 46, 50-51; while Canart, based on the reproductions he had access to, was able to identify just one low pseudo-ligature in the script of the manuscript, for epsilon-ny, we are now able to say that others are present as well, as epsilon-omega, epsilon-pi, confirming his assumption that the script of GCC 403 belongs to this style).
The text is written in black ink.
Hand a: passim in the margins there are notes in a Greek minuscule script, probably contemporary with the main scribe, see e.g. pp. [24], [38], [242].

Hand b: passim in the margins there are brief notes in a Greek minuscule script, by a hand with a low graphic education, probably a Western hand not very skilled n the writing of Greek. See e.g. pp. 43, 59, 147.

Hand c: in the margins and between lines throughout there are notes in Latin and in Greek by Robert Grosseteste Grosseteste, Robert, 1175?-1253 (among others, Callus 1955, p 135; Buchthal 1983, p. 80; Weyl Carr 1987, p. 117) see e.g. pp. [2]-[4]. Similar notes are present also in MS CUL, Ff.1.24 , also owned by him.
Hand d: on pp. , 3-5, 239-241, 258-284, 289-309, between lines, there are translations in Latin of words, by another, later, hand.

decoDesc.decoNote:
A full-page miniature of the evangelist precedes the Gospels of Mark and Luke:
p. 142: Mark is seated, in the act of thinking; his right hand lies on a scroll open on his right knee. On the background there are a building, coloured in red, on the left, and a desk, in yellow and red, with an open scroll, on the right; the background is filled with gold. The frame of the miniature is blue with white patterns, and red edge
p. 238: Luke is seated, he has an open scroll in his left hand, and is bending onwards to consult a scroll open on a desk. On the background there are a building, coloured in grey and white, on the left, and a desk, in red, on the right; the ground is filled with gold. The frame of the miniature is blue with white patterns, and red edge.
On pp. 1, 143, 239, 371 rectangular spaces with a frame in red ink have been left blank; probably they should have contained decorated headpieces.

Major initials, at the beginning of the Gospels, are decorated with various motifs:
p.1 zoomorphic contoured initial in red ink (snake)
p. 143 figure contoured initial in red ink (nude young figure with a scroll)
p. 239 zoomorphic contoured initial in red ink (bird and fishes, a hand)
p. 371 zoomorphic contoured initial in red ink (dragon and birds)

additions.p: In the upper margin of p. 1 there is a note of ownership of the Franciscan House in Oxford, written in brown ink (see Provenance). In the upper margin, in a black ink, is written the number 14. The number 94 is written in brown ink in the left margin. In the frame, which probably should have contained a decorated headpiece, is written a note concerning the donation to Gonville and Caius College (see Acquisition). In the right margin has been pasted a paper strip with a Greek alphabet written vertically. In the right margin, near the space left for the headpiece, Quatuor Evangelia scripta 1806.

In the right margin of p. [303], in a light brown ink, is written the name mg Bryngkeley. On p. 470, after the end of the Gospel of John, is written, by another hand, in a light brown ink, the name Βρηνκελει διδασκαλως . In both cases this is Richard Brinkley, the Cambridge Franciscan who received the manuscript on loan in the early 16th c.
There are notes in the margins throughout by a later hand, in Latin, indicating the beginning of chapters, see e.g. p. 47.

binding.p: Early modern western binding. Full leather cover over millboard. Blind tooling on both boards (frame), gold tooling on the boards' edges. On the spine there is gold tooling with title The Four Gospels in Greek, and two paper labels with the two shelfmarks 412 (in red) and 4[0]3 (in black). 210 150 ca. 70-80
binding.condition: Rebacked. Corners covered in new leather.

origin.p: The manuscript was copied in the 13th c., before 1253, when Robert Grosseteste, who was its owner, died. The place of origin of the manuscript is uncertain ( Canart 1981, pp. 50-51), although script and decoration belong to styles typical of manuscripts produced in the areas of Cyprus and Palestine.

provenance.p: The manuscript was owned by Robert Grosseteste (1175?-1253) Grosseteste, Robert, 1175?-1253 , Bishop of Lincoln. In the manuscript there are notes in his hand.

After his death, the manuscript came in the possession of the Franciscan House in Oxford, the note of ownership is still visible on p. 1, Quatuor Ewang. in gr. | Iste liber est de communitate fratrum minorum Oxonie ( James [1908, p. 469] dates the script to the 13th c.).

In the early 16th c. it was lent to the Cambridge Franciscan Richard Brinkley, warden of the Grey Friars (see Scrivener 2010, pp. xxviii-xxix), see a note continuing the mark of ownership on p. 1, Concessus et accomodatus fratri Richardi Bryngkeley magistro. His name is written in the right margin of p. [303], and, in Greek, on p. 470. The manuscript was never returned to the Franciscan House.

history.acquisition: The Grey Friars' House was dissolved in 1538, and the manuscript may have come into the hands of Hatcher at this time (this is the hypothesis advanced by Scrivener 2010, p. xxix). It was donated to Gonville and Caius College in 1567 by Hatcher, Thomas, -1583 Thomas Hatcher , see the note in brown ink on p. [1], Novum Testamentum | Graecum | quod Collegio de Goneville | et Caius dono dedit Thomas | Hatcher | artium Magister; under the note, in a different, black, ink was added the date of the donation, 1567. On the left pastedown is pasted the Gonville and Caius College bookplate (with handwritten shelfmark in red ink, 412, and in black ink, 403).

recordHist.source: Description (2021) partly draws on M. R. James, A descriptive catalogue of the Manuscripts in the Library of Gonville and Caius College, vol. 2, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 1908, pp. 469-470.
